<li role="presentation"><a href='?term="Shoulder%20Elbow"[jour]' class="usa-link" role="menuitem" data-add-to-search="true">Add to search</a></li>
</ul></nav></section><section class="front-matter"><div class="ameta p font-secondary font-xs">
<hgroup><h1>Postoperative stiffness after reverse total shoulder arthroplasty</h1></hgroup><div class="cg p">
<a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Ghoraishian%20M"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id1"><span class="name western">Mohammad Ghoraishian</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id1">
<h3><span class="name western">Mohammad Ghoraishian</span></h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Department of Orthopaedic Surgery, Rothman Orthopaedic Institute, Sidney Kimmel Medical College, Thomas Jefferson University, Philadelphia, PA, USA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Ghoraishian%20M"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Mohammad Ghoraishian</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Hill%20BW"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id2"><span class="name western">Brian W Hill</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id2">
<h3><span class="name western">Brian W Hill</span></h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Department of Orthopaedic Surgery, Rothman Orthopaedic Institute, Sidney Kimmel Medical College, Thomas Jefferson University, Philadelphia, PA, USA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Hill%20BW"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Brian W Hill</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Nicholson%20T"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id3"><span class="name western">Thema Nicholson</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id3">
<h3><span class="name western">Thema Nicholson</span></h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Department of Orthopaedic Surgery, Rothman Orthopaedic Institute, Sidney Kimmel Medical College, Thomas Jefferson University, Philadelphia, PA, USA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Nicholson%20T"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Thema Nicholson</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Ramsey%20ML"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id4"><span class="name western">Matthew L Ramsey</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id4">
<h3><span class="name western">Matthew L Ramsey</span></h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Department of Orthopaedic Surgery, Rothman Orthopaedic Institute, Sidney Kimmel Medical College, Thomas Jefferson University, Philadelphia, PA, USA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Ramsey%20ML"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Matthew L Ramsey</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Williams%20GR"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id5"><span class="name western">Gerald R Williams Jr</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id5">
<h3><span class="name western">Gerald R Williams Jr</span></h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Department of Orthopaedic Surgery, Rothman Orthopaedic Institute, Sidney Kimmel Medical College, Thomas Jefferson University, Philadelphia, PA, USA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Williams%20GR"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Gerald R Williams Jr</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Namdari%20S"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id6"><span class="name western">Surena Namdari</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id6">
<h3><span class="name western">Surena Namdari</span></h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Department of Orthopaedic Surgery, Rothman Orthopaedic Institute, Sidney Kimmel Medical College, Thomas Jefferson University, Philadelphia, PA, USA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Namdari%20S"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Surena Namdari</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1,</sup><sup>✉</sup>
</div>
<ul class="d-buttons inline-list">
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="aip_a" aria-expanded="false">Author information</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="anp_a" aria-expanded="false">Article notes</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="clp_a" aria-expanded="false">Copyright and License information</button></li>
</ul>
<div class="d-panels font-secondary-light">
<div id="aip_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div class="p" id="aff1-1758573220967312">
<sup>1</sup>Department of Orthopaedic Surgery, Rothman Orthopaedic Institute, Sidney Kimmel Medical College, Thomas Jefferson University, Philadelphia, PA, USA</div>
<div class="author-notes p"><div class="fn" id="corresp1-1758573220967312">
<sup>✉</sup><p class="display-inline">Surena Namdari, Department of Orthopaedic Surgery, Rothman Orthopaedic Institute, Thomas Jefferson University, 925 Chestnut St, 5th floor, Philadelphia, PA 19107, USA. Email: <span>surena.namdari@rothmanortho.com</span></p>
</div></div>
</div>
<div id="anp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="notes p"><section id="historyarticle-meta1" class="history"><p>Received 2020 Jun 3; Revised 2020 Sep 28; Accepted 2020 Sep 28; Issue date 2022 Apr.</p></section></div></div>
<div id="clp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div>© 2020 The British Elbow &amp; Shoulder Society</div>
<div class="p"><a href="/about/copyright/" class="usa-link">PMC Copyright notice</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<div>PMCID: PMC8899328  PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35265180/" class="usa-link">35265180</a>
</div>
</div></section></section><section aria-label="Article content"><section class="body main-article-body"><section class="abstract" id="abstract1"><h2>Abstract</h2>
<section id="sec1"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Purpose</h3>
<p>The purpose of this study was to evaluate the rate and risk factors for stiffness after reverse shoulder arthroplasty and the ramifications on the patient-reported outcomes.</p></section><section id="sec2"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Method</h3>
<p>A consecutive series of patients who underwent reverse shoulder arthroplasty were prospectively followed for one year. Passive range of motion was measured preoperatively and at regular intervals postoperatively. Patients with passive forward elevation of less than 100° or passive external rotation of less than 30° were defined as stiff. Radiographic parameters and postoperative patient-reported outcome scores were collected.</p></section><section id="sec3"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Results</h3>
<p>Seventy-six patients were available for review. The prevalence of postoperative stiffness following reverse shoulder arthroplasty was 47% at three months, 31% at six months, and 25% at one year. Preoperative shoulder stiffness was associated with three-month postoperative stiffness only. In patients with one-year stiffness, smaller (<em>p</em> = 0.03) and less lateralized glenospheres (<em>p</em> = 0.024) were more common. Stiffness was not associated with one-year patient-reported outcome scores.</p></section><section id="sec4"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Conclusion</h3>
<p>Stiffness is common after reverse shoulder arthroplasty and often improves at one-year after surgery. Implant design and selection may be important determinants of passive range of motion. While stiffness does not appear to influence patient-reported outcome scores, one of four patients will potentially have stiffness one year following reverse shoulder arthroplasty.</p>
<p><strong>Level of evidence:</strong> Level III; retrospective study.</p></section><section id="kwd-group1" class="kwd-group"><p><strong>Keywords:</strong> Shoulder stiffness, reverse total shoulder arthroplasty, risk factors, patient outcomes, implant design, patient satisfaction</p></section></section><section id="sec1-1758573220967312"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Introduction</h2>
<p>Active shoulder range of motion (ROM) needed for functional daily activities has been quantified.<sup>
<a href="#bibr1-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr1-1758573220967312">1</a>
</sup> While patients can have better passive motion than active ROM, active motion can only be as good as passive motion. Stiffness, or a limitation in passive motion, has been studied after rotator cuff repair surgery and less than 5% of patients undergoing rotator cuff repair undergo secondary surgery for stiffness.<sup>
<a href="#bibr2-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr2-1758573220967312">2</a>
</sup> In a large study evaluating the complications following 1673 anatomic arthroplasties, stiffness accounted for approximately 13% of the complications.<sup>
<a href="#bibr3-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr3-1758573220967312">3</a>
</sup> Further, stiffness has been shown to be a major reason for dissatisfaction and failure after shoulder arthroplasty. Hasan et al. reported that 74% of the 139 patients with unsatisfactory outcomes after hemiarthroplasty and anatomic total shoulder arthroplasty complained of stiffness.<sup>
<a href="#bibr4-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr4-1758573220967312">4</a>
</sup></p>
<p>In reverse shoulder arthroplasty (RSA), stiffness may be a soft-tissue related problem but may also be directly related to bony or implant impingement. Knowing the prevalence of shoulder stiffness after RSA and the influencing factors may impact preoperative patient counseling, intraoperative decisions, and postoperative rehabilitation. The purpose of this study was to determine the rate of early stiffness after RSA, predictive factors, and the influence of early stiffness on final postoperative ROM and patient-reported outcomes.</p></section><section id="sec2-1758573220967312"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Methods</h2>
<p>After institutional review board (IRB) approval, a database of two studies that prospectively collected data on a consecutive series of patients who underwent RSA was reviewed. Passive forward elevation (PFE) and passive external rotation (PER) at the side were collected preoperatively, three months, six months, and one year postoperatively in a standardized fashion by one of three trained research coordinators using a goniometer. PER with the arm at the side of &lt;30° or passive forward flexion of &lt;100° was considered stiff.<sup><a href="#bibr5-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr5-1758573220967312">5</a>–<a href="#bibr7-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr7-1758573220967312">7</a></sup> Internal rotation was not routinely measured. Patients with revision arthroplasty, post-infectious sequelae, intraoperative or postoperative complications, acute fracture indication, and patients who underwent revision surgery during the first postoperative year were excluded.</p>
<p>All surgeries were performed through a deltopectoral approach by six surgeons involved. Two implants were used, the Zimmer<sup>R</sup> Trabecular Metal™ Reverse (Zimmer-Biomet, Warsaw, IN; 45 patients) and Integra<sup>R</sup> Titan™ Reverse (Integra Life Sciences, Austin, TX; 31 patients) shoulder systems. The Zimmer TM Reverse system has a humeral liner and spacer combination from +0 to +18 mm and a 150° neck-shaft angle. It has 36 and 40 mm concentric glenospheres with +2.5 mm lateralization on the baseplate. The Integra Titan Reverse system has liners from +0 to +9 and a 142° neck-shaft angle. It has a 38-mm concentric or eccentric glenosphere with +2 and +5 lateralization. Patient demographics (age, sex, body mass index, side of surgery, hand dominance), previous shoulder surgery, preoperative diagnosis, and intraoperative data (glenosphere size, lateralization, spacer and polyethylene size, humeral component retroversion, and subscapularis status after surgery) were collected. The combination of spacer and polyethylene liner size (mm) was recorded. Preoperative and one-year postoperative patient-reported outcome scores (PROs) (American shoulder and elbow surgeons score (ASES)/Single assessment numeric evaluation (SANE) and Simple shoulder test (SST)) were collected. While patients who underwent reoperation were excluded from analysis, intraoperative and postoperative complications were collected.</p>
<section id="sec3-1758573220967312"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Radiological evaluation</h3>
<p>The acromiohumeral distance (AHD) and lateral humeral offset (LHO) were measured on preoperative and postoperative radiographs as described previously<sup>
<a href="#bibr8-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr8-1758573220967312">8</a>
</sup> (<a href="#fig1-1758573220967312" class="usa-link">Figure 1</a>). AHD was measured as the perpendicular distance between the most lateral portion of the undersurface of the acromion and a line parallel to the superior border of the greater tuberosity. LHO was measured as the horizontal distance from the previously drawn AHD line to the most lateral projection of the superior border of the greater tuberosity. The difference between postoperative and preoperative LHO was recorded. The difference of AHD was recorded as distalization. Notching was graded at one-year after surgery according to Sirveaux et al.<sup>
<a href="#bibr9-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr9-1758573220967312">9</a>
</sup> Measurements and grading were evaluated by a fellowship-trained, shoulder surgeon who was blinded to the ROM at the time of radiographic evaluation and not involved with the surgery.
</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="fig1-1758573220967312"><h4 class="obj_head">Figure 1.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=8899328_10.1177_1758573220967312-fig1.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/aa76/8899328/68f3aad924c3/10.1177_1758573220967312-fig1.jpg" loading="lazy" height="411" width="755" alt="Figure 1."></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/fig1-1758573220967312/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>(a) Preoperative and (b) postoperative radiograph demonstrating the acromiohumeral distance (AHD) and lateral humeral offset (LHO).</p></figcaption></figure></section><section id="sec4-1758573220967312"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Statistical analysis</h3>
<p>Chi-square, Fisher’s exact test, T-test, and nonparametric McNemar test were used for data analysis using Statistical Package for the Social Sciences (SPSS) version 17. <em>p</em> value &lt;0.05 was considered to indicate statistical significance.</p></section></section><section id="sec5-1758573220967312"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Results</h2>
<p>From 79 primary RSA patients included, 3 were excluded, leaving 76 patients for analysis (96%). One patient had a dislocation at six weeks postoperatively that was revised with liner exchange. Two others were lost to follow-up. Forty-nine percent (37/76) were men and the mean body mass index was 30 ± 6 (range: 19–50). Arthroplasty was performed on the dominant side in 70% (53/76) of cases. The diagnosis for surgery was cuff tear arthropathy (CTA) in 67 (88%), posttraumatic arthritis in 7 (9%), and primary osteoarthritis with irreparable rotator cuff tear in 2 (3%). Thirty patients (39%) had a previous shoulder surgery (24 rotator cuff repair, 3 proximal humerus fracture fixation, 1 bictif tenodesis, and 1 Putti-Platt operation).</p>
<section id="sec6-1758573220967312"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Preoperative evaluation</h3>
<p>Twenty-one patients (28%) met stiffness criteria preoperatively. Mean preoperative PFE was 112° ± 41° (range: 30°–180°) in the stiff cohort and 146° ± 21° (range; 100°–180°) in the non-stiff cohort (<em>p</em> &lt; 0.001). Mean preoperative PER was 21° ± 17° (range: −10°–60°) versus 44° ± 12° (range: 30°–90°) in the stiff and non-stiff groups, respectively (<em>p</em> &lt; 0.001). The distribution of the patients was similar in the preoperatively stiff and non-stiff groups regarding age, sex, etiology, BMI, and hand dominance (<em>p</em> &gt; 0.05; <a href="#table1-1758573220967312" class="usa-link">Table 1</a>). Preoperative and postoperative ASES, SST, and SANE scores were not different between the preoperative stiff and non-stiff groups (<em>p</em> &gt; 0.05).
</p>
