<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/table1-1758573220967312/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<div class="tw-foot p"><div class="fn" id="table-fn1-1758573220967312"><p>ASES: American shoulder and elbow surgeons score; BMI; body mass index; CTA: cuff tear arthropathy; IY: 1-year; OR: Operating Room; OA: Osteoarthritis; SANE: single assessment numeric evaluation; SST: simple shoulder test.</p></div></div></section></section><section id="sec7-1758573220967312"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Three-month follow-up</h3>
<p>Thirty-five patients (47%) were considered stiff at the three-month clinical visit. Sixty-two percent (13/21) of the preoperatively stiff group were still considered to be stiff at three months, while 42% (22/53) of the preoperative non-stiff group had three-month stiffness (<em>p</em> = 0.016). Mean PFE was 124° ± 29° (range: 70°–175°) in the stiff and 142° ± 26° (range: 100°–170°) in the non-stiff group (<em>p</em> = 0.007). Mean PER was 12° ± 9° (range: 0°–25°) in stiff versus 38° ± 8° (range: 30°–50°) in non-stiff group (<em>p</em> &lt; 0.001). Stiff patients were older (72 ± 7 (range: 55–83) vs. 67 ± 8 (range: 54–86), <em>p</em> = 0.011) and more likely to have had dominant-sided surgery (60% vs. 18%, <em>p</em> = 0.001). There was no difference in gender, BMI, and previous surgical history between the two groups at this time point. Patients who had an implant with a larger glenosphere (<em>p</em> = 0.016) and a more lateralized glenosphere (<em>p</em> = 0.028) had less stiffness (<a href="#table2-1758573220967312" class="usa-link">Table 2</a>).
</p>
