<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/table2-1758573220967312/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section><p>The management of the subscapularis differed between patients. Seventy-five percent of the patients underwent subscapularis repair based on surgeon preference and ability to repair the subscapularis. This did not appear to effect stiffness as 46% of the repair group and 52% of the non-repaired group were stiff at three months, which was not statistically significant (<em>p</em> = 0.683). Radiographically (<a href="#table3-1758573220967312" class="usa-link">Table 3</a>), non-stiff patients had significantly greater LHO (4.2 ± 8.8 mm vs. − 2.4 ± 11 mm, <em>p</em> = 0.016).

</p>
