<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/table3-1758573220967312/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<div class="tw-foot p"><div class="fn" id="table-fn3-1758573220967312"><p>HAD: humeral acromial distance; LHO: lateral humeral offset.</p></div></div></section></section><section id="sec8-1758573220967312"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Six-month follow-up</h3>
<p>Twenty-two patients (31%) were considered stiff at the six-month clinical visit. From the 35 patients with three-month stiffness, 21 (60%) remained stiff at six months. From the three-month non-stiff patients, only one developed stiffness at six months. Mean PFE was 141° ± 29° (range: 45°–170°) in the stiff cohort and 147° ± 18° (range: 110°–170°) in the non-stiff group (<em>p</em> = 0.311). Mean PER was 13° ± 7° (range: 0°–25°) in the stiff group versus 42° ± 12° (range: 30°–8°) in the non-stiff group (<em>p</em> &lt; 0.001).</p></section><section id="sec9-1758573220967312"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">One-year follow-up</h3>
<p>From the 68 patients who presented for the one-year follow-up, 17 patients (25%) were considered stiff. All but one of these patients was stiff at the three-month clinical follow-up. Out of 35 patients who had stiffness at the three-month follow-up, 16 (46%) were no longer considered stiff at one year. One-year stiffness was not associated with preoperative stiffness (<em>p</em> = 0.83). Average PFE at one year postoperatively was 136° ± 32° (range: 45°–180°) in the stiff group compared with 151° ± 18° (range: 110°–180°) in the non-stiff cohort (<em>p</em> = 0.021). Average PER at one year postoperatively was 16° ± 7° (range: 0°–25°) in stiff versus 40° ± 9° (range: 30°–60°) in non-stiff group (<em>p</em> &lt; 0.001). Patients who had an implant with a larger glenosphere had less stiffness at one-year (<em>p</em> = 0.03). Glenospheres were less lateralized in the one-year stiff group (average 2.8 ± 0.8 vs. 3.6 ± 1.3 mm, <em>p</em> = 0.024) compared with the non-stiff cohort. twenty-three percent of the patients in the stiff group had subscapularis repair compared to 21% in the non-stiff group (<em>p</em> = 0.84). Forty-seven percent (8/17) of the patients in the stiff group demonstrated scapular notching at one-year (two were grade 2 and six were grade 1) compared to 16% in the non-stiff group (8/49; one was grade 2 and seven were grade 1) (<em>p</em> = 0.02). Other radiographic parameters and PROs (ASES, SST, SANE) were not different between the stiff and non-stiff groups at one year after surgery (<em>p</em> &gt; 0.05) (Table 4).</p></section></section><section id="sec10-1758573220967312"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Discussion</h2>
<p>Various criteria have been used to define shoulder stiffness, including percentage of the preoperative or contralateral shoulder ROM, total deficit of all motion planes, patient’s dissatisfaction with postoperative motion, and different ranges in flexion, abduction, internal and external rotation.<sup><a href="#bibr10-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr10-1758573220967312">10</a>–<a href="#bibr13-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr13-1758573220967312">13</a></sup> In our study, 47% of the patients after RSA had PER &lt; 30° or PFE &lt;100° at the three-month clinical follow-up and 25% continued to have decreased passive ROM in either plane at one year. Preoperative shoulder stiffness was found to be associated with three-month postoperative shoulder stiffness but not with stiffness one year postoperatively. Additionally, postoperative stiffness was less common with use of larger and more lateralized glenospheres.</p>
<p>In about half of the patients (54%) with early stiffness in this study, the ROM limitations did not resolve at the one-year follow-up. This clinical finding is in contrast to the patients identified with stiffness following rotator cuff repair.<sup><a href="#bibr6-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr6-1758573220967312">6</a>,<a href="#bibr14-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr14-1758573220967312">14</a></sup> With rotator cuff repair, stiffness is thought to be a soft tissue limitation. Although this cannot be discounted based on the findings of this study, it appears that stiffness after RSA may have an implant-related etiology and may not resolve in many patients. In a retrospective case series of 76 patients treated with RSA, Garcia et al. reported only 11.8% of the patients complained of stiffness at a mean 31.6 months of follow-up.<sup>
<a href="#bibr15-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr15-1758573220967312">15</a>
</sup></p>
<p>Langohr et al., in their cadaveric study on reverse arthroplasty glenosphere diameters of 38 and 42 mm, did not report any difference in PER with an increase in glenosphere diameter.<sup>
<a href="#bibr16-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr16-1758573220967312">16</a>
</sup> This is in contrast to the clinical study by Mollon et al. who evaluated 297 shoulder arthroplasties and found larger glenosphere diameter was associated with greater active forward flexion and external rotation.<sup>
<a href="#bibr17-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr17-1758573220967312">17</a>
</sup> A virtual analysis of impingement free ROM showed that an increase in glenosphere diameter from 36 to 39 increased external rotation as well.<sup>
<a href="#bibr18-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr18-1758573220967312">18</a>
</sup> In the current study, the patients without stiffness at three months and one year had larger and more lateralized glenospheres. Greiner et al. reported better active external rotation in 17 patients with lateralized glenospheres compared to 17 patients with nonlateralized glenospheres in a prospective randomized study utilizing “bio-RSA” and RSA without bone graft.<sup>
<a href="#bibr18-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr18-1758573220967312">18</a>
</sup> Similarly, Keener et al. found that optimal ROM of RSA was achieved with 10-mm baseplate lateralization via advanced software evaluating ROM after computed tomography scans.<sup>
<a href="#bibr19-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr19-1758573220967312">19</a>
</sup> Improved active external rotation has been attributed to more tension in rotator cuff muscles in lateralized glenospheres’ designs and also part of the posterior deltoid acting as an external rotator.<sup><a href="#bibr16-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr16-1758573220967312">16</a>,<a href="#bibr19-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr19-1758573220967312">19</a>,<a href="#bibr20-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr20-1758573220967312">20</a></sup> In another virtual analysis model, Li et al. reported more impingement free external rotation in lateralized glenospheres.<sup>
<a href="#bibr21-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr21-1758573220967312">21</a>
</sup> It appears that while lateralized implants may allow for greater rotator cuff tension and deltoid activation, the improvement in active motion that is observed may also be a result of impingement free motion.</p>
<p>With increased glenosphere lateralization, some clinicians worry about an increase in the torque and shear forces on the glenoid component, leading to early glenoid loosening.<sup>
<a href="#bibr22-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr22-1758573220967312">22</a>
</sup> Lawrence et al. performed a systematic review of 13 studies including 349 patients comparing the complications with a medialized Grammont style glenosphere and a lateralized glenosphere design.<sup>
<a href="#bibr20-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr20-1758573220967312">20</a>
</sup> The authors reported an increased glenoid loosening rate in the lateralized group (8.8% lateralized vs. 1.8% Grammont, <em>p</em> = 0.003); however, the analysis included lateralized designs prior to the implementation of peripheral locking screws. Additionally, the current study reported greater rates of scapular notching at three months and one year in the stiff group. Given the association between scapular notching and a more medialized center of rotation, this finding is not surprising.<sup><a href="#bibr20-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr20-1758573220967312">20</a>,<a href="#bibr23-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr23-1758573220967312">23</a></sup></p>
<p>Interestingly, the difference in the PROs obtained at one-year follow-up was not significant between the stiff and non-stiff cohorts. Considering our result that patients in the three month and one-year stiff group commonly had diminished PER at the side; it seems that external rotation at side after RSA does not substantially influence patient functional scores. These findings reflect the similar results by Kiet et al. in their case control study evaluating the outcomes after TSA and RSA.<sup>
<a href="#bibr24-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr24-1758573220967312">24</a>
</sup> The authors reported no differences in ASES scores or visual analog scale between 47 TSA patients and 53 RSA patients despite a significant increase in external rotation in the patients who received a TSA. Also, there was not a difference in stiffness based on subscapularis repair. This is similar to the report by Vourazeris et al.<sup>
<a href="#bibr25-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr25-1758573220967312">25</a>
</sup> where external rotation was similar between the patients with or without subscapularis repair (24° vs. 26°, respectively) after RSA. The lack of association between stiffness and outcomes scores in the current study could indicate that our definition of stiffness was not strict enough to capture true functional limitations. Alternatively, the outcome measures used may not be sensitive enough to reflect actual limitations caused by stiffness in external rotation and/or flexion.</p>
<p>This study has several limitations. This was a retrospective review of a two prior prospectively collected studies. Certain variables such as intraoperative motion, active motion, implant type, rehabilitation, and patient satisfaction were unable to be controlled. Currently there is not a defined criterion for stiffness following shoulder arthroplasty. The definition utilized in this study (&lt;30° PER or &lt;100° PFE) was based on studies reporting stiffness after rotator cuff repair<sup><a href="#bibr6-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr6-1758573220967312">6</a>,<a href="#bibr14-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr14-1758573220967312">14</a></sup> and ROM in activities of daily living after shoulder arthroplasty.<sup>
<a href="#bibr26-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr26-1758573220967312">26</a>
</sup> Further research is needed to define these criteria and the selected parameters may not be ideal. The passive ROM measured during the clinical encounters was standardized and obtained by trained research personnel not associated with the surgery however, these measurements were not based on patient-perceived stiffness and may be the reason we found no differences in the cohorts. Potentially, collecting patient-perceived stiffness would have allowed us to find the differences between the cohorts. In assessing PER, the version of the humeral component may be critical. Unfortunately, implants were placed based on surgeon preference and not uniform in this study. We did attempt to find if humeral version placement did have an effect on PER but were unable to find an association. Additionally, our study was limited to one-year follow-up. This may be sufficient however as prior research on outcomes after RSA report patient-reported outcomes and ROM plateau at one year postoperatively.<sup>
<a href="#bibr27-1758573220967312" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr27-1758573220967312">27</a>
</sup></p></section><section id="sec11-1758573220967312"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Conclusion</h2>
<p>Stiffness following RSA is common and often improves at one-year after surgery. The implant design and selection may be important determinants of passive ROM. While stiffness does not appear to influence patient-reported outcomes, one of four patients will have stiffness that persists beyond one-year follow-up after RSA.</p></section><section id="ack1" class="ack"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Acknowledgments</h2>
